{"title_page": "Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada<br /><small>{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627\u062f\u06c1}}</small>\n| native_name = \n| image       = Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada Portrait.jpg\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1961|3|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Jauharabad]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| education   = Masters in Journalism from University of Punjab, Lahore, Pakistan\n| occupation  = Journalist\n| title       = The First Blind Journalist of [[Pakistan]], Columnist Nawaiwaqt, Chief Editor Akhbare Urdu\n| children    = 2 Sons\n| relatives   =\n| nationality = [[Pakistan]]i\n| credits     = APNS Best Urdu Column Award Holder. Volunteer Work on PWDs \n}}\n\n'''Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627\u062f\u06c1}}}}; born 27 March 1961) is a Pakistani journalist, radio anchor, and socio-political analyst most prominently known as the '''First Blind Journalist of Pakistan'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://unesco.org.pk/education/idpd_seminar.html|title = Seminar on International Day of Persons with Disabilities 2012|date = |accessdate = 1 August 2014|website = United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|publisher = UNESCO Islamabad|last = |first = }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|url = http://www.na.gov.pk/uploads/documents/1393399576_800.pdf|title = November 2013 - January 2014|date = Jan 2014|journal = The National Assembly of Pakistan Gazette|accessdate = 1 August 2014|page = 9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.facebook.com/USEFP/posts/746092198786678|date = 21 July 2014|accessdate = 1 August 2014|website = United States Educational Foundation in Pakistan|publisher = USEFP, Facebook|title = It is an honor to have Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada; The First Blind Journalist of Pakistan cover our Pre-departure Orientation.}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url = https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/presspakistan/L-1rcYPm-GU|title = PFUJ flays NLA Ban on first blind Journalists and Columnist of Pakistan|last = Shamsul Islam|first = Naz|date = 18 July 2010|work = Press Pakistan|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.na.gov.pk/en/print-press.php?id=754|title = Sense of Worth and Self Respect for All of Us: Says NA Speaker|last = Sardar Ayaz|first = Sadiq|date = December 17, 2013|work = National Assembly of Pakistan Press|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.app.com.pk/en_/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=255445&Itemid=2|title = Govt committed to provide opportunities for special people: Speaker|date = December 17, 2014|work = Associated Press of Pakistan|accessdate = 1 August 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063939/http://www.app.com.pk/en_/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=255445&Itemid=2|archivedate = 4 March 2016}}</ref> He is currently Chief Editor of Monthly Akhbar-e-Urdu<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://nlpd.gov.pk/uakhbareurdu/october2013/index.html|title = Editorial Board of Akhbar-e-Urdu|date = October 2013|journal = Monthly Akhbar-e-Urdu|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref> and also writes columns for Urdu newspapers including Daily [[Nawaiwaqt]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.nawaiwaqt.com.pk/E-Paper/islamabad/2014-07-29/page-15|title = Saaf Saaf - Telling the Truth|date = 29 July 2014|work = Daily Nawaiwaqt|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref> He has been recognized and awarded by many NGOs and prominent personalities of Pakistan including but not limited to the Former President of Pakistan, Mr. [[Asif Ali Zardari]]. He is one of the few Pakistani Journalists whose articles and analysis were being monitored by the Global Intelligence Company [[Stratfor]] in the emails leaked by [[WikiLeaks]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url = https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/76/769817_us-pakistan-pakistan-commentary-says-us-attacked-army-post.html|title = US/PAKISTAN - Pakistan commentary says US attacked army post to avenge ex-envoy's resignation|date = 11 March 2013|accessdate = 1 August 2014|website = The Global Intelligence Files|publisher = WikiLeaks.org}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and early career ==\nSyed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada was born in the city of [[Jauharabad]], District [[Khushab]], [[Pakistan]] in March 1961. He was partially sighted at birth but due to the progression of [[Glaucoma]] became visually impaired soon after. His education consisted of inclusive institutions that did not have any special facilities to accommodate Visually Impaired students. He did his Masters in Journalism from the [[University of the Punjab]], Lahore in 1985. Sardar Pirzada faced a lot of oppression and bias due to his impairment and people in his field of work refused to judge him on merit alone (by his own accounts).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://saafsaaf.blogspot.com/p/about-me.html|title=About Me|accessdate=1 August 2014|website=The First Blind Journalist of Pakistan Writes 'Saaf Saaf' - Telling the Truth}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his post graduation in journalism, Pirzada entered mainstream media and started working as reporter and sub editor for national dailies and weeklies including ''[[Daily Jang]]'', ''Daily Jasarat'', ''Daily Mashriq'' and ''Weekly Istaqlal''. He has also worked as the editor of the English monthly entitled ''The Diplomat'', a publication designed for the diplomatic community of Pakistan. Sometime in 1988 Sardar Ahmed Pirzada joined the government organization [[National Language Authority of Pakistan|National Language Authority Of Pakistan]] (now NLPD, Ministry of Information, Broadcasting and National Heritage of Govt of Pakistan) as the Public Relations Officer. He became the editor of Monthly Akhbar-e-Urdu in 2003 and became Editor-in-Chief of the same in 2011. During this time has published a five-volume book series entitled ''Pakistan Mein Urdu'' (Urdu in Pakistan).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Adopting the mantle of the First Blind Journalist of Pakistan ==\nPirzada has been active in mainstream Journalism before he graduated, his earliest works date back to 1985. He is the mentor of the Pakistani Journalist and Columnist Javed Chudhry.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.javed-chaudhry.com/tag/syed-sardar-ahmed-pirzada/|title=Blind Man Searching for Justice in a Blind Community|date=17 July 2010|accessdate=13 August 2014|publisher=Javed Chaudhry|work=Daily Express News|last=|first=}}</ref> Early in his career he faced oppression and lack of acceptance in mainstream journalism due to the fact that he was visually impaired. He adopted the mantle of the First Blind Journalist of Pakistan (TFBJP) sometime in 2007. According to his own accounts, the reason he adopted the title of \"the First Blind Journalist of Pakistan\" was to turn his only weakness (the stigma of being blind) into his strength. He joined the national Urdu daily of Pakistan, ''[[Nawaiwaqt]]'' in May 2007 and currently still writes as a columnist. Many other young visually impaired journalists have followed his role model into mainstream journalism. Following his role He started working as a Radio anchor in a socio-political talk show, \"Sunrise key Mehman\" on Sunrise FM 97 in August 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saafsaaf.blogspot.com/p/radio-show.html|title=Radio Show|date=May 2, 2013|accessdate=13 August 2014|website=Saaf Saaf - Telling the Truth|publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref> He left the Radio Station sometime in July 2013.\n\nPirzada has appeared on various political talk shows on television, including ''[[Capital Talk]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pakistanherald.com/program/7763/capital-talk-august-11-2011-hamid-mir-exclusive-conversation-with-some-prominent-blind-personalities.|title=Capital Talk on Thursday, August 11, 2011|date=|accessdate=16 August 2014|website=Pakistan Herald|publisher =Gibralter Information Technologies |last=|first=}}</ref> His articles have gained recognition and prominence in the past few years and have been the cause of Suo Motto Notices by the Courts of Pakistan on social issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nawaiwaqt.com.pk/E-Paper/islamabad/2013-07-23/page-3|title=Supreme Court Takes Suo Motto Notice on the Column of Sardar Pirzada (Translation)|last=|first=|date=July 23, 2013|work=Nawaiwaqt|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> His published analysis on the political scenarios of Pakistan were being monitored, translated and included in the surveillance revealed by the emails leaked by [[WikiLeaks]] on [[Stratfor]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Controversy and ban ===\nIn July 2010, a ban was placed on Sardar Pirzada by National Language Authority of Pakistan to not partake in any journalistic activities. This ban was met with widespread criticism by media community of Pakistan, with very prominent lobbies rallying to his side.<ref name=\":4\" /> This included the [[Pakistan Federal Union of Journalists]] (PFUJ) who strongly condemned the action in a Press Release to the Media, quoting the blatant violation of Pirzada's rights as under Article 19 of the Constitution of Pakistan.<ref name=\":1\" /> The ban was ultimately reversed under pressure from the Media.\n\n== Notable achievements and work ==\nPirzada has received numerous awards and accolades for his writings, analysis and work in journalism.\n\n=== APNS Best Column Award (Urdu) 2012 ===\n\nPirzada was awarded the prestigious [[All Pakistan Newspapers Society|All Pakistan Newspaper Society]] Best Urdu Column Award for the year 2012. This award was conferred upon him by the now former President of Pakistan, [[Asif Ali Zardari]] at the 22nd Journalistic Awards Ceremony, Presidency of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.dawn.com/news/711072/journalists-advertisers-given-awards-apns-urged-to-look-into-salary-issue|title = Journalists, advertisers given awards: APNS urged to look into salary issue|last = Staff Reporter|first = |date = April 16, 2012|work = Dawn|accessdate = 13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-102435-22nd-APNS-Awards-ceremony-to-be-held-on-16th|title = 22nd APNS Awards ceremony to be held on 16th|last = |first = |date = April 11, 2012|work = The News International|accessdate = 13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Other awards ===\n\n* NPC Gold Medal Award for Services in Journalism. Conferred by [[Abdul Qadeer Khan|Dr. A. Q. Khan]] on behalf of [[Nazaria-i-Pakistan Trust|Nazria Pakistan Council]] on 27 March 2013 .<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=201909|title = NPC Gold Medal Awards - Dr A Q Khan urges youth to work for Pakistan\u2019s progress|last = Ansari|first = Ashraf|date = March 28, 2013|work = Pakistan Observer|accessdate = 13 August 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140813130338/http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=201909|archivedate = 13 August 2014}}</ref>\n* Cholistan Award 2012 for Services in Media. Conferred by Cholistan Development Council on 14 April 2012.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Press Club Pakistan Lifetime Achievement Award and Honorary Lifetime Membership. Conferred by NPC President Farooq Faisal in Annual General Body meeting on 12 December 2013.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Work on PWDs and disability movement ===\nSardar has been working for the welfare of PWDs for several years on a completely voluntary basis. He has been striving for the representation of Persons With Disabilities in the Parliament and has made significant progress towards the same. He has been present in the assembly when resolutions based on his work were brought on the floor<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=227140|title = Opportunities for special people|last = APP|date = 18 December 2013|work = Pakistan Observer|accessdate = 13 August 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140813135202/http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=227140|archivedate = 13 August 2014}}</ref> He has also helped in motivational programs in Pakistan (for the disabled) and has worked alongside many NGOs to rehabilitate PWDs and to spread awareness on the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.maati.tv/2012/05/14/revolving-5th-vasakh-film-festival-sindh-day-2/|title = Revolving 5th Vasakh Film Festival Sindh \u2013 Day 2|date = 2012-05-14|accessdate = 13 August 2014|website = Maati.TV|publisher = MAATI TV|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120525140913/http://www.maati.tv/2012/05/14/revolving-5th-vasakh-film-festival-sindh-day-2/|archivedate = 25 May 2012}}</ref> He has also drafted theories about PWDs and has presented them on more than one occasion. The more notable of these is the Disabled by Association theory.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://hhrd.pk/rehabnow/2012/11/vdieo-message-syed-sardar-ahmed-pirzada-columnist-daily-nawa-i-waqt/|title = Vdieo Message Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada, Columnist Daily Nawa-i-Waqt|date = 20 November 2012|accessdate = 13 August 2014|website = National Conference on Comprehensive Rehabilitation & Empowerment of Persons with Disabilities.|publisher = Rehab Now|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pirzada, Syed Sardar Ahmed}}\n[[Category:Pakistani male journalists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani radio presenters]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Pakistan]]\n[[Category:University of the Punjab alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada<br /><small>{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627\u062f\u06c1}}</small>\n| native_name = \n| image       = Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada Portrait.jpg\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1961|3|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Jauharabad]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| education   = Masters in Journalism from University of Punjab, Lahore, Pakistan\n| occupation  = Journalist\n| title       = The First Blind Journalist of [[Pakistan]], Columnist Nawaiwaqt, Chief Editor Akhbare Urdu\n| children    = 2 Sons\n| relatives   =\n| nationality = [[Pakistan]]i\n| credits     = APNS Best Urdu Column Award Holder. Volunteer Work on PWDs \n}}\n\n'''Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627\u062f\u06c1}}}}; born 27 March 1961) is a Pakistani journalist, radio anchor, and socio-political analyst most prominently known as the '''First Blind Journalist of Pakistan'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://unesco.org.pk/education/idpd_seminar.html|title = Seminar on International Day of Persons with Disabilities 2012|date = |accessdate = 1 August 2014|website = United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|publisher = UNESCO Islamabad|last = |first = }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|url = http://www.na.gov.pk/uploads/documents/1393399576_800.pdf|title = November 2013 - January 2014|date = Jan 2014|journal = The National Assembly of Pakistan Gazette|accessdate = 1 August 2014|page = 9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.facebook.com/USEFP/posts/746092198786678|date = 21 July 2014|accessdate = 1 August 2014|website = United States Educational Foundation in Pakistan|publisher = USEFP, Facebook|title = It is an honor to have Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada; The First Blind Journalist of Pakistan cover our Pre-departure Orientation.}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url = https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/presspakistan/L-1rcYPm-GU|title = PFUJ flays NLA Ban on first blind Journalists and Columnist of Pakistan|last = Shamsul Islam|first = Naz|date = 18 July 2010|work = Press Pakistan|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.na.gov.pk/en/print-press.php?id=754|title = Sense of Worth and Self Respect for All of Us: Says NA Speaker|last = Sardar Ayaz|first = Sadiq|date = December 17, 2013|work = National Assembly of Pakistan Press|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.app.com.pk/en_/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=255445&Itemid=2|title = Govt committed to provide opportunities for special people: Speaker|date = December 17, 2014|work = Associated Press of Pakistan|accessdate = 1 August 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063939/http://www.app.com.pk/en_/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=255445&Itemid=2|archivedate = 4 March 2016}}</ref> He is currently Chief Editor of Monthly Akhbar-e-Urdu<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://nlpd.gov.pk/uakhbareurdu/october2013/index.html|title = Editorial Board of Akhbar-e-Urdu|date = October 2013|journal = Monthly Akhbar-e-Urdu|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref> and also writes columns for Urdu newspapers including Daily [[Nawaiwaqt]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.nawaiwaqt.com.pk/E-Paper/islamabad/2014-07-29/page-15|title = Saaf Saaf - Telling the Truth|date = 29 July 2014|work = Daily Nawaiwaqt|accessdate = 1 August 2014}}</ref> He has been recognized and awarded by many NGOs and prominent personalities of Pakistan including but not limited to the Former President of Pakistan, Mr. [[Asif Ali Zardari]]. He is one of the few Pakistani Journalists whose articles and analysis were being monitored by the Global Intelligence Company [[Stratfor]] in the emails leaked by [[WikiLeaks]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url = https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/76/769817_us-pakistan-pakistan-commentary-says-us-attacked-army-post.html|title = US/PAKISTAN - Pakistan commentary says US attacked army post to avenge ex-envoy's resignation|date = 11 March 2013|accessdate = 1 August 2014|website = The Global Intelligence Files|publisher = WikiLeaks.org}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and early career ==\nSyed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada was born in the city of [[Jauharabad]], District [[Khushab]], [[Pakistan]] in March 1961. He was partially sighted at birth but due to the progression of [[Glaucoma]] became visually impaired soon after. His education consisted of inclusive institutions that did not have any special facilities to accommodate Visually Impaired students. He did his Masters in Journalism from the [[University of the Punjab]], Lahore in 1985. Sardar Pirzada faced a lot of oppression and bias due to his impairment and people in his field of work refused to judge him on merit alone (by his own accounts).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://saafsaaf.blogspot.com/p/about-me.html|title=About Me|accessdate=1 August 2014|website=The First Blind Journalist of Pakistan Writes 'Saaf Saaf' - Telling the Truth}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his post graduation in journalism, Pirzada entered mainstream media and started working as reporter and sub editor for national dailies and weeklies including ''[[Daily Jang]]'', ''Daily Jasarat'', ''Daily Mashriq'' and ''Weekly Istaqlal''. He has also worked as the editor of the English monthly entitled ''The Diplomat'', a publication designed for the diplomatic community of Pakistan. Sometime in 1988 Sardar Ahmed Pirzada joined the government organization [[National Language Authority of Pakistan|National Language Authority Of Pakistan]] (now NLPD, Ministry of Information, Broadcasting and National Heritage of Govt of Pakistan) as the Public Relations Officer. He became the editor of Monthly Akhbar-e-Urdu in 2003 and became Editor-in-Chief of the same in 2011. During this time has published a five-volume book series entitled ''Pakistan Mein Urdu'' (Urdu in Pakistan).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Adopting the mantle of the First Blind Journalist of Pakistan ==\nPirzada has been active in mainstream Journalism before he graduated, his earliest works date back to 1985. He is the mentor of the Pakistani Journalist and Columnist Javed Chudhry.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.javed-chaudhry.com/tag/syed-sardar-ahmed-pirzada/|title=Blind Man Searching for Justice in a Blind Community|date=17 July 2010|accessdate=13 August 2014|publisher=Javed Chaudhry|work=Daily Express News|last=|first=}}</ref> Early in his career he faced oppression and lack of acceptance in mainstream journalism due to the fact that he was visually impaired. He adopted the mantle of the First Blind Journalist of Pakistan (TFBJP) sometime in 2007. According to his own accounts, the reason he adopted the title of \"the First Blind Journalist of Pakistan\" was to turn his only weakness (the stigma of being blind) into his strength. He joined the national Urdu daily of Pakistan, ''[[Nawaiwaqt]]'' in May 2007 and currently still writes as a columnist. Many other young visually impaired journalists have followed his role model into mainstream journalism. Following his role He started working as a Radio anchor in a socio-political talk show, \"Sunrise key Mehman\" on Sunrise FM 97 in August 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saafsaaf.blogspot.com/p/radio-show.html|title=Radio Show|date=May 2, 2013|accessdate=13 August 2014|website=Saaf Saaf - Telling the Truth|publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref> He left the Radio Station sometime in July 2013.\n\nPirzada has appeared on various political talk shows on television, including ''[[Capital Talk]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pakistanherald.com/program/7763/capital-talk-august-11-2011-hamid-mir-exclusive-conversation-with-some-prominent-blind-personalities.|title=Capital Talk on Thursday, August 11, 2011|date=|accessdate=16 August 2014|website=Pakistan Herald|publisher =Gibralter Information Technologies |last=|first=}}</ref> His articles have gained recognition and prominence in the past few years and have been the cause of Suo Motto Notices by the Courts of Pakistan on social issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nawaiwaqt.com.pk/E-Paper/islamabad/2013-07-23/page-3|title=Supreme Court Takes Suo Motto Notice on the Column of Sardar Pirzada (Translation)|last=|first=|date=July 23, 2013|work=Nawaiwaqt|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> His published analysis on the political scenarios of Pakistan were being monitored, translated and included in the surveillance revealed by the emails leaked by [[WikiLeaks]] on [[Stratfor]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Controversy and ban ===\nIn July 2010, a ban was placed on Sardar Pirzada by National Language Authority of Pakistan to not partake in any journalistic activities. This ban was met with widespread criticism by media community of Pakistan, with very prominent lobbies rallying to his side.<ref name=\":4\" /> This included the [[Pakistan Federal Union of Journalists]] (PFUJ) who strongly condemned the action in a Press Release to the Media, quoting the blatant violation of Pirzada's rights as under Article 19 of the Constitution of Pakistan.<ref name=\":1\" /> The ban was ultimately reversed under pressure from the Media.\n\n== Notable achievements and work ==\nPirzada has received numerous awards and accolades for his writings, analysis and work in journalism.\n\n=== APNS Best Column Award (Urdu) 2012 ===\n\nPirzada was awarded the prestigious [[All Pakistan Newspapers Society|All Pakistan Newspaper Society]] Best Urdu Column Award for the year 2012. This award was conferred upon him by the now former President of Pakistan, [[Asif Ali Zardari]] at the 22nd Journalistic Awards Ceremony, Presidency of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.dawn.com/news/711072/journalists-advertisers-given-awards-apns-urged-to-look-into-salary-issue|title = Journalists, advertisers given awards: APNS urged to look into salary issue|last = Staff Reporter|first = |date = April 16, 2012|work = Dawn|accessdate = 13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-102435-22nd-APNS-Awards-ceremony-to-be-held-on-16th|title = 22nd APNS Awards ceremony to be held on 16th|last = |first = |date = April 11, 2012|work = The News International|accessdate = 13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Other awards ===\n\n* NPC Gold Medal Award for Services in Journalism. Conferred by [[Abdul Qadeer Khan|Dr. A. Q. Khan]] on behalf of [[Nazaria-i-Pakistan Trust|Nazria Pakistan Council]] on 27 March 2013 .<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=201909|title = NPC Gold Medal Awards - Dr A Q Khan urges youth to work for Pakistan\u2019s progress|last = Ansari|first = Ashraf|date = March 28, 2013|work = Pakistan Observer|accessdate = 13 August 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140813130338/http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=201909|archivedate = 13 August 2014}}</ref>\n* Cholistan Award 2012 for Services in Media. Conferred by Cholistan Development Council on 14 April 2012.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Press Club Pakistan Lifetime Achievement Award and Honorary Lifetime Membership. Conferred by NPC President Farooq Faisal in Annual General Body meeting on 12 December 2013.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Work on PWDs and disability movement ===\nSardar has been working for the welfare of PWDs for several years on a completely voluntary basis. He has been striving for the representation of Persons With Disabilities in the Parliament and has made significant progress towards the same. He has been present in the assembly when resolutions based on his work were brought on the floor<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=227140|title = Opportunities for special people|last = APP|date = 18 December 2013|work = Pakistan Observer|accessdate = 13 August 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140813135202/http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=227140|archivedate = 13 August 2014}}</ref> He has also helped in motivational programs in Pakistan (for the disabled) and has worked alongside many NGOs to rehabilitate PWDs and to spread awareness on the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.maati.tv/2012/05/14/revolving-5th-vasakh-film-festival-sindh-day-2/|title = Revolving 5th Vasakh Film Festival Sindh \u2013 Day 2|date = 2012-05-14|accessdate = 13 August 2014|website = Maati.TV|publisher = MAATI TV|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120525140913/http://www.maati.tv/2012/05/14/revolving-5th-vasakh-film-festival-sindh-day-2/|archivedate = 25 May 2012}}</ref> He has also drafted theories about PWDs and has presented them on more than one occasion. The more notable of these is the Disabled by Association theory.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://hhrd.pk/rehabnow/2012/11/vdieo-message-syed-sardar-ahmed-pirzada-columnist-daily-nawa-i-waqt/|title = Vdieo Message Syed Sardar Ahmed Pirzada, Columnist Daily Nawa-i-Waqt|date = 20 November 2012|accessdate = 13 August 2014|website = National Conference on Comprehensive Rehabilitation & Empowerment of Persons with Disabilities.|publisher = Rehab Now|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pirzada, Syed Sardar Ahmed}}\n[[Category:Pakistani male journalists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani radio presenters]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Pakistan]]\n[[Category:University of the Punjab alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syed_Sardar_Ahmed_Pirzada"}
{"title_page": "Jacob Landau (artist)", "text_new": "{{other people||Jacob Landau (disambiguation){{!}}Jacob Landau}}\n{{Short description|American painter}}\n'''Jacob Landau''' (December 17, 1917 &ndash; November 24, 2001) was an American artist best known for his evocative works on the human condition. Typically, his works address the [[Great Depression]], [[World War II]], and the impact of technology and politics on individuals and their surroundings. Landau's works can be found in the permanent collections of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], the [[Library of Congress]], the [[Museum of Modern Art]], and the [[National Gallery]].\n\n==Biography==\nLandau was born December 17, 1917, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. By the age of three he began drawing everything around him. When he was 12, he began studying at the Graphic Sketch Club, now the [[Samuel Fleisher Memorial]]. At the age of 17, Landau\u2019s illustrations for Kipling\u2019s ''[[Jungle Book]]'' won a competition in ''Scholastic Magazine''. He won the competition the following year as well. In 1935, Landau received a scholarship from the Museum School of Industrial Art (today the [[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)|University of the Arts]]) to study illustration, printmaking and painting.<ref name=\"Stein\">{{cite web|last=Stein|first=Judith|title=Jacob Landau: Old Man Mad About Drawing|url=http://judithestein.com/jacob-landau-old-man-mad-about-drawing|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref> After his graduation in 1939,  Landau moved to [[New York City]] where he experimented with a variety of styles, treatments and media. His first phase as a professional artist included illustrating books and magazines.\n\nIn 1943, Landau was drafted into the armed forces, serving two years overseas in the [[Mediterranean Theater of Operations|Mediterranean Theater]]. In the army, Landau served in a number of capacities which utilized his artistic talents. His service in Italy included work as the art editor, photographer, and reporter of ''[[At Ease]]'', a special services magazine. After his discharge in 1946, Landau used the [[G.I. Bill]] to further study art.\n\nLandau spent a year (1948-1949) at New York's [[New School for Social Research]] before moving to Paris with his wife, Frances, and young son to study at the [[Academie Julian]] and the [[Academie de la Grande Chaumiere]]. While in Paris, Landau met printmaker [[Leonard Baskin]], who taught him the medium of woodcuts.<ref name=Stein />\n\nFrom 1954-1957 Landau taught at the [[Philadelphia College of Art]] before moving to [[Pratt Institute]] where he would teach for over 20 years. During his time at Pratt, Landau helped to establish the University Without Walls program, in which students worked closely with instructors to gain hands-on experience. In 1975, Landau became a faculty member of the [[Artist Teacher Institute]], a 10-day summer residency program sponsored by the [[New Jersey State Council on the Arts]].\n\nIn addition to his art and teaching, Landau was very involved in the community. He was active in many different organizations including: Alliance for Arts Education, [[American Humanist Association]], Association for Humanistic Psychology, Coalition for Nuclear Disarmament, International Arts Association, [[Jewish Federation]], Linkage Project, New Jersey School for the Arts, Printmaking Council, and World Futures Society. In 1974 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member and became a full Academician in 1979.\n\nLandau and his wife Frances lived in [[Roosevelt, New Jersey]] as part of a small community of artists. There he built a [[geodesic dome]] which was created as an art studio. His wife died in 1993 of [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. They had two sons, Jonas and Stefan.\n\nJacob Landau died on November 24, 2001, at the age of 85, and is buried in the Roosevelt Cemetery near his friends [[Ben Shahn]] and [[Gregorio Prestopino]].<ref name=Obit>{{cite web|last=Denicola|first=Linda|title=Artist Jacob Landau Gone, but his work survives|url=http://tri.gmnews.com/news/2002-01-10/Front_page/010.html|publisher=Tri-Town News|accessdate=May 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913000139/http://tri.gmnews.com/news/2002-01-10/Front_Page/010.html|archive-date=September 13, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  After his death, the Jacob Landau Institute was formed to preserve his legacy, share his unique philosophy of education, and nurture individual artists.<ref name=Institute />\n\n==Artwork==\nLandau's art communicates his consciousness of humankind's predicament, its beauty and its horror.<ref name=Yarosh>{{cite web|title=James Yarosh Gallery|url=http://jamesyarosh.com/jacob070409_2.html|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref> Growing up during the [[Great Depression]] and having been profoundly affected by [[The Holocaust]], Landau's work expresses the self-inflicted human turmoil of the 20th century. He often drew from biblical or literary sources, presenting unpleasant topics in a way that emphasized the unlimited possibilities of peace and greater understanding. Existential philosopher Walter Kauffman described Landau's work as \"unmistakenly modern and at the same time in the tradition of Goya and Blake.\"<ref name=Stein />\n\n==Select exhibitions==\nLandau's work has been exhibited in over 30 one-man and 200 group shows, both nationally and internationally.<ref name=Institute>{{cite web|last=Jacob Landau Institute|title=About the Author|url=http://www.jacoblandau.org/theartist.html|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n*\u201cLe Drame Quotidien,\u201d Galerie Paul Lebar, Paris, 1952 Apr \u2013 May\n*\u201cThe Insiders,\u201d [[Cober Gallery]], New York City, 1960 Nov 8-26\n*\u201cThree Artists View the Human Condition,\u201d [[New Jersey State Museum]], 1968 June \u2013 Sept\n*\u201cHuman Concern/Personal Torment,\u201d [[Whitney Museum]], New York City, 1969 Oct \u2013 Nov\n*\u201cKingdom of Dreams,\u201d [[Associated American Artists]], New York City, 1970? Feb 2-21\n*\u201cJacob Landau: The Graphic Work,\u201d [[New Jersey State Museum]], 1981 June \u2013 Aug\n*\u201cJacob Landau: A Print Retrospective,\u201d [[Philadelphia Art Alliance]], 1981 Sept \u2013 Oct\n*\u201cInternational Printmaking Invitational,\u201d The Art Gallery, [[California State University, San Bernardino|California State College at San Bernardino]], 1983 Apr \u2013 May\n*\u201cFrom the Capital to the Cape: A Celebration of New Jersey Artists,\u201d [[Noyes Museum]], Oceanville, NJ, 1983 June \u2013 Sept\n*\u201cDreams and Nightmares: Utopian Visions in Modern Art,\u201d [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden|Hirschhorn Museum]], Washington, DC, 1983 \u2013 1984\n*\u201cThe Prophetic Quest,\u201d Temple Judea Museum of Kenneth Israel, Elkins Park, PA, 1995 Mar \u2013 June\n*\u201cOld Man Mad about Drawing,\u201d [[Monmouth University]], West Long Branch, NJ, 1997 Feb 7-26\n*\u201cUnlimited Possibilities: Jacob Landau Works on Paper 1950 \u2013 2000,\u201d Erdman Gallery, [[Princeton Theological Seminary]], Princeton, NJ, 2001 Oct \u2013 Dec\n\n==Book illustration==\n\nIn addition to his numerous paintings, lithographs, sketches and drawings, Landau illustrated books. Below are some examples:\n\n*Watkins, L. A. ''Rhumbo''. New York: Grosset and Dunlap, 1937.\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe|Poe, Edgar Allan]]. ''Gold Bug''. New York: Macmillan, 1953.\n*Beals, Carleton. ''Adventure on the Western Sea''. New York: Holt, 1956.\n*Call, Hughie. ''Rising Arrow''. New York: Viking, 1955.\n*[[Benjamin Appel|Appel, Benjamin]]. ''Man and Magic''. New York: Pantheon, 1966.\n*Friedlander, Albert H. ''Out of the Whirlwind''. New York: [[Union of American Hebrew Congregations]], 1968.\n*[[E. T. A. Hoffmann|Hoffmann, E. T. A.]] ''Tales of E. T. A. Hoffmann''. Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1972.\n*Herrstrom, David Sten. ''Appearing by Daylight''. Huntington, WV: Aegina Press, 1989.\n*Herrstrom, David Sten. ''Jonah's Disappearance''. Tarzana, CA: 1992.\n\n==Collections of Landau's work==\n\nThe Jacob Landau Institute was founded to preserve the memory and legacy of Jacob Landau. The Institute has established two major cooperative agreements to this end. [[Drew University]] Library permanently houses the Jacob Landau Archive, which includes his papers, artwork, and books. The Library is currently working to organize and preserve the materials in the Archive for the use and longevity of Landau's legacy. The Jacob Landau Institute works in conjunction with [[Monmouth University]] in [[West Long Branch, New Jersey]] to create educational programs that have far reaching benefits for the artistic community and general population of [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth County]] and beyond.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jacoblandau.org Jacob Landau Institute]\n* [http://www.monmouth.edu/jewish_cultural_studies/curricularmaterials.asp Monmouth University Jewish Cultural Studies Program]\n* [http://www.drew.edu/library/special-collections-archives/special-collections/jacob-landau-collection/ Jacob Landau Collection at Drew University Library]\n* {{LCAuth|n80104693|Jacob Landau|17|}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Landau, Jacob}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:People from Roosevelt, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Artists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of the Arts (Philadelphia) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Jacob Landau (disambiguation){{!}}Jacob Landau}}\n{{Short description|American painter}}\n'''Jacob Landau''' (December 17, 1917 &ndash; November 24, 2001) was an American artist best known for his evocative works on the human condition. Typically, his works address the [[Great Depression]], [[World War II]], and the impact of technology and politics on individuals and their surroundings. Landau's works can be found in the permanent collections of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], the [[Library of Congress]], the [[Museum of Modern Art]], and the [[National Gallery]].\n\n==Biography==\nLandau was born December 17, 1917, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. By the age of three he began drawing everything around him. When he was 12, he began studying at the Graphic Sketch Club, now the [[Samuel Fleisher Memorial]]. At the age of 17, Landau\u2019s illustrations for Kipling\u2019s ''[[Jungle Book]]'' won a competition in ''Scholastic Magazine''. He won the competition the following year as well. In 1935, Landau received a scholarship from the Museum School of Industrial Art (today the [[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)|University of the Arts]]) to study illustration, printmaking and painting.<ref name=\"Stein\">{{cite web|last=Stein|first=Judith|title=Jacob Landau: Old Man Mad About Drawing|url=http://judithestein.com/jacob-landau-old-man-mad-about-drawing|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref> After his graduation in 1939,  Landau moved to [[New York City]] where he experimented with a variety of styles, treatments and media. His first phase as a professional artist included illustrating books and magazines.\n\nIn 1943, Landau was drafted into the armed forces, serving two years overseas in the [[Mediterranean Theater of Operations|Mediterranean Theater]]. In the army, Landau served in a number of capacities which utilized his artistic talents. His service in Italy included work as the art editor, photographer, and reporter of ''[[At Ease]]'', a special services magazine. After his discharge in 1946, Landau used the [[G.I. Bill]] to further study art.\n\nLandau spent a year (1948-1949) at New York's [[New School for Social Research]] before moving to Paris with his wife, Frances, and young son to study at the [[Academie Julian]] and the [[Academie de la Grande Chaumiere]]. While in Paris, Landau met printmaker [[Leonard Baskin]], who taught him the medium of woodcuts.<ref name=Stein />\n\nFrom 1954-1957 Landau taught at the [[Philadelphia College of Art]] before moving to [[Pratt Institute]] where he would teach for over 20 years. During his time at Pratt, Landau helped to establish the University Without Walls program, in which students worked closely with instructors to gain hands-on experience. In 1975, Landau became a faculty member of the [[Artist Teacher Institute]], a 10-day summer residency program sponsored by the [[New Jersey State Council on the Arts]].\n\nIn addition to his art and teaching, Landau was very involved in the community. He was active in many different organizations including: Alliance for Arts Education, [[American Humanist Association]], Association for Humanistic Psychology, Coalition for Nuclear Disarmament, International Arts Association, [[Jewish Federation]], Linkage Project, New Jersey School for the Arts, Printmaking Council, and World Futures Society. In 1974 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member and became a full Academician in 1979.\n\nLandau and his wife Frances lived in [[Roosevelt, New Jersey]] as part of a small community of artists. There he built a [[geodesic dome]] which was created as an art studio. His wife died in 1993 of [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. They had two sons, Jonas and Stefan.\n\nJacob Landau died on November 24, 2001, at the age of 85, and is buried in the Roosevelt Cemetery near his friends [[Ben Shahn]] and [[Gregorio Prestopino]].<ref name=Obit>{{cite web|last=Denicola|first=Linda|title=Artist Jacob Landau Gone, but his work survives|url=http://tri.gmnews.com/news/2002-01-10/Front_page/010.html|publisher=Tri-Town News|accessdate=May 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913000139/http://tri.gmnews.com/news/2002-01-10/Front_Page/010.html|archive-date=September 13, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  After his death, the Jacob Landau Institute was formed to preserve his legacy, share his unique philosophy of education, and nurture individual artists.<ref name=Institute />\n\n==Artwork==\nLandau's art communicates his consciousness of humankind's predicament, its beauty and its horror.<ref name=Yarosh>{{cite web|title=James Yarosh Gallery|url=http://jamesyarosh.com/jacob070409_2.html|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref> Growing up during the [[Great Depression]] and having been profoundly affected by [[The Holocaust]], Landau's work expresses the self-inflicted human turmoil of the 20th century. He often drew from biblical or literary sources, presenting unpleasant topics in a way that emphasized the unlimited possibilities of peace and greater understanding. Existential philosopher Walter Kauffman described Landau's work as \"unmistakenly modern and at the same time in the tradition of Goya and Blake.\"<ref name=Stein />\n\n==Select exhibitions==\nLandau's work has been exhibited in over 30 one-man and 200 group shows, both nationally and internationally.<ref name=Institute>{{cite web|last=Jacob Landau Institute|title=About the Author|url=http://www.jacoblandau.org/theartist.html|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n*\u201cLe Drame Quotidien,\u201d Galerie Paul Lebar, Paris, 1952 Apr \u2013 May\n*\u201cThe Insiders,\u201d [[Cober Gallery]], New York City, 1960 Nov 8-26\n*\u201cThree Artists View the Human Condition,\u201d [[New Jersey State Museum]], 1968 June \u2013 Sept\n*\u201cHuman Concern/Personal Torment,\u201d [[Whitney Museum]], New York City, 1969 Oct \u2013 Nov\n*\u201cKingdom of Dreams,\u201d [[Associated American Artists]], New York City, 1970? Feb 2-21\n*\u201cJacob Landau: The Graphic Work,\u201d [[New Jersey State Museum]], 1981 June \u2013 Aug\n*\u201cJacob Landau: A Print Retrospective,\u201d [[Philadelphia Art Alliance]], 1981 Sept \u2013 Oct\n*\u201cInternational Printmaking Invitational,\u201d The Art Gallery, [[California State University, San Bernardino|California State College at San Bernardino]], 1983 Apr \u2013 May\n*\u201cFrom the Capital to the Cape: A Celebration of New Jersey Artists,\u201d [[Noyes Museum]], Oceanville, NJ, 1983 June \u2013 Sept\n*\u201cDreams and Nightmares: Utopian Visions in Modern Art,\u201d [[Hirschhorn Museum]], Washington, DC, 1983 \u2013 1984\n*\u201cThe Prophetic Quest,\u201d Temple Judea Museum of Kenneth Israel, Elkins Park, PA, 1995 Mar \u2013 June\n*\u201cOld Man Mad about Drawing,\u201d [[Monmouth University]], West Long Branch, NJ, 1997 Feb 7-26\n*\u201cUnlimited Possibilities: Jacob Landau Works on Paper 1950 \u2013 2000,\u201d Erdman Gallery, [[Princeton Theological Seminary]], Princeton, NJ, 2001 Oct \u2013 Dec\n\n==Book illustration==\n\nIn addition to his numerous paintings, lithographs, sketches and drawings, Landau illustrated books. Below are some examples:\n\n*Watkins, L. A. ''Rhumbo''. New York: Grosset and Dunlap, 1937.\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe|Poe, Edgar Allan]]. ''Gold Bug''. New York: Macmillan, 1953.\n*Beals, Carleton. ''Adventure on the Western Sea''. New York: Holt, 1956.\n*Call, Hughie. ''Rising Arrow''. New York: Viking, 1955.\n*[[Benjamin Appel|Appel, Benjamin]]. ''Man and Magic''. New York: Pantheon, 1966.\n*Friedlander, Albert H. ''Out of the Whirlwind''. New York: [[Union of American Hebrew Congregations]], 1968.\n*[[E. T. A. Hoffmann|Hoffmann, E. T. A.]] ''Tales of E. T. A. Hoffmann''. Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1972.\n*Herrstrom, David Sten. ''Appearing by Daylight''. Huntington, WV: Aegina Press, 1989.\n*Herrstrom, David Sten. ''Jonah's Disappearance''. Tarzana, CA: 1992.\n\n==Collections of Landau's work==\n\nThe Jacob Landau Institute was founded to preserve the memory and legacy of Jacob Landau. The Institute has established two major cooperative agreements to this end. [[Drew University]] Library permanently houses the Jacob Landau Archive, which includes his papers, artwork, and books. The Library is currently working to organize and preserve the materials in the Archive for the use and longevity of Landau's legacy. The Jacob Landau Institute works in conjunction with [[Monmouth University]] in [[West Long Branch, New Jersey]] to create educational programs that have far reaching benefits for the artistic community and general population of [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth County]] and beyond.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jacoblandau.org Jacob Landau Institute]\n* [http://www.monmouth.edu/jewish_cultural_studies/curricularmaterials.asp Monmouth University Jewish Cultural Studies Program]\n* [http://www.drew.edu/library/special-collections-archives/special-collections/jacob-landau-collection/ Jacob Landau Collection at Drew University Library]\n* {{LCAuth|n80104693|Jacob Landau|17|}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Landau, Jacob}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:People from Roosevelt, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Artists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of the Arts (Philadelphia) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "WomenArtistUpdates", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelect exhibitions:Hirschhorn Museum", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacob_Landau_(artist)"}
